## 🧠 1. Stop just “looking at data” — start questioning it

Most people do:

* `.head()`
* `.describe()`
* a few plots

That’s surface-level.

You should be asking:

* *What patterns are actually meaningful vs random?*
* *Is this correlation real or coincidence?*
* *What would I bet money on here?*

👉 This shift matters more than any library.

---

## 📊 2. Get very strong at Pandas (seriously)

Not just basics — you should be comfortable with:

* `groupby()` (multi-level, aggregations)
* `pivot_table()`
* `merge()` / `join()` (real-world datasets are messy)
* handling missing data (`fillna`, `interpolate`)
* datetime operations (`dt` accessor)

If you can’t manipulate data fast → analysis becomes slow and shallow.

---

## 📈 3. Visualization that actually explains something

Using:

* Matplotlib
* Seaborn

But don’t just plot for the sake of it.

You should know:

* when to use histogram vs boxplot vs scatter
* how to spot outliers, skew, trends
* how to tell a story with charts

👉 A good plot = instant insight.

---

## 📉 4. Statistics (this is where most people are weak)

This is what separates “data analyst” from “data viewer”.

You need:

* mean vs median (and when each lies)
* variance / standard deviation
* distributions (normal, skewed)
* correlation vs causation
* hypothesis testing (t-test basics)

Core idea:
👉 *Can you prove something, or are you just observing it?*

---

## 🤖 5. Intro to modeling (even for analysis)

Not full ML — just enough to test ideas.

Using:

* scikit-learn

Know:

* linear regression (for trends)
* logistic regression (for classification)
* feature importance

👉 Helps answer: *“what actually drives this outcome?”*

---

## 🧹 6. Data cleaning (this is 60% of real work)

You should be comfortable with:

* inconsistent formats
* duplicates
* outliers
* bad/missing values

Real datasets are messy — your resume project already hints at this, so go deeper here.

---

## 🗃️ 7. SQL thinking (even inside Python)

Even if you use Pandas:

* think in joins
* filtering
* aggregations

Because real-world data is rarely in one clean CSV.

---

## 📦 8. Working with real datasets (this is crucial)

Don’t just use toy datasets.

Use:

* messy CSVs
* APIs
* large datasets

👉 Your H1-B project is actually perfect for this — push it further:

* feature engineering
* bias detection
* trend analysis over time

---

## 🔥 What most people miss (this is important)

They learn tools but ignore:

* storytelling
* asking the right question
* validating results

That’s why many “data analysts” don’t stand out.

---

## 🎯 To simplify everything into a roadmap

1. Master Pandas deeply
2. Learn visualization properly
3. Add statistics
4. Practice on messy real data
5. Use basic ML to validate insights

